1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,300
[SPEAKER_00] - 1989. As the Iron Curtain fell, Eastern European countries quickly integrate into a globalizing

2
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:22,460
[SPEAKER_00] world economy. Within just three decades, Central, Eastern, and Southeastern European economies,

3
00:00:22,460 --> 00:00:28,920
[SPEAKER_00] also called CESI countries, have doubled trade as a share of GDP. Foreign direct investment

4
00:00:28,920 --> 00:00:34,740
[SPEAKER_00] into the region has increased seven-fold. Global supply chains have created more efficient

5
00:00:34,740 --> 00:00:41,500
[SPEAKER_00] and specialized production by drawing on countries' relative strength. CESI countries have quickly

6
00:00:41,500 --> 00:00:48,560
[SPEAKER_00] integrated into global supply chains. That means they are importing intermediate goods from elsewhere

7
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:56,100
[SPEAKER_00] and integrating these into the goods they are exporting. By 2018, a quarter of CESI exports

8
00:00:56,100 --> 00:01:03,380
[SPEAKER_00] are imported inputs from other countries. And in turn, over half of CESI exports are used

9
00:01:03,380 --> 00:01:11,319
[SPEAKER_00] as inputs for production by other countries. For example, European businesses have been outsourcing

10
00:01:11,319 --> 00:01:18,219
[SPEAKER_00] or shifting production to CESI countries to take advantage of lower-cost skilled labor, including

11
00:01:18,219 --> 00:01:25,079
[SPEAKER_00] the German, French, and Italian automobile industry, which outsources to the Czech Republic, Hungary,

12
00:01:25,079 --> 00:01:30,159
[SPEAKER_00] Poland, Romania, and Slovakia.

13
00:01:30,159 --> 00:01:36,299
[SPEAKER_00] These regional supply chains contribute to strong trade and foreign direct investment linkages between

14
00:01:36,299 --> 00:01:47,079
[SPEAKER_00] advanced European countries and CESI. 61% of CESI exports go to advanced European countries, and another 13% to CESI countries.

15
00:01:47,079 --> 00:01:54,359
[SPEAKER_00] For foreign direct investment, 86% comes from advanced European countries.

16
00:01:54,359 --> 00:02:03,719
[SPEAKER_00] And with this integration come clear benefits: lower transaction costs, greater production efficiency,

17
00:02:03,719 --> 00:02:09,080
[SPEAKER_00] faster technology diffusion, and faster cross-country convergence in living standards.

18
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:16,520
[SPEAKER_00] Living standards in CESI continue to rise closer to those in the advanced European countries.

19
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:22,360
[SPEAKER_00] Despite these gains, threats to globalization have begun to appear.

20
00:02:22,360 --> 00:02:28,360
[SPEAKER_00] While globalization has helped to lift more than a billion people out of extreme poverty,

21
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:35,639
[SPEAKER_00] during the pandemic, those threats increased as shortages of intermediate inputs and labor, together with jammed logistical systems,

22
00:02:35,639 --> 00:02:48,919
[SPEAKER_00] disrupted supply chains.

23
00:02:48,919 --> 00:02:54,919
[SPEAKER_00] Motor vehicle manufacturers reported shortages of intermediate goods, which were still being felt at the end of 2022.

24
00:02:54,919 --> 00:03:04,199
[SPEAKER_00] Suppliers' delivery times shot up sharply while they have since come down.

25
00:03:04,199 --> 00:03:12,199
[SPEAKER_00] The specialization in supply chains, which fostered production efficiency, became a source of fragility.

26
00:03:12,199 --> 00:03:23,479
[SPEAKER_00] The war and reduced gas deliveries by Russia led to major realignments in energy and agricultural commodity markets.

27
00:03:23,479 --> 00:03:32,759
[SPEAKER_00] In particular, Europe quickly achieved a sharp reduction for natural gas imports through determined policy action.

28
00:03:32,759 --> 00:03:41,960
[SPEAKER_00] Together, the pandemic, the war, and global geopolitical tensions have led to a greater number of protectionist measures.

29
00:03:41,960 --> 00:03:49,639
[SPEAKER_00] High-tech sectors linked to national security or strategic competition are among the most affected.

30
00:03:49,639 --> 00:03:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] Europe is no exception to these trends.

31
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,919
[SPEAKER_00] The EU has started limiting the entry of foreign firms while encouraging domestic production.

32
00:03:58,919 --> 00:04:03,319
[SPEAKER_00] Especially in strategic sectors, such as semiconductors.

33
00:04:03,319 --> 00:04:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] European exporters also face rising barriers.

34
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,360
[SPEAKER_00] For example, in the US, new green subsidies favor local production.

35
00:04:12,360 --> 00:04:16,600
[SPEAKER_00] Such green subsidies can help achieve climate goals,

36
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:20,920
[SPEAKER_00] but can also distort investment decisions and global supply relationships.

37
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:27,079
[SPEAKER_00] In this changing landscape, firms are increasingly looking to relocate production

38
00:04:27,079 --> 00:04:31,959
[SPEAKER_00] to make supply chains more resilient and less vulnerable to geopolitical tensions.

39
00:04:31,959 --> 00:04:42,199
